      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''T.R.? He's No T.R.'' (editorial, Feb. 11):</p>
        <p>That President Bush is no T.R. goes without saying. In 2000, when two oilmen squeaked into office, we had every reason to fear an unprecedented disregard for the natural world, energy efficiency and renewable energy.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''T.R.? He's No T.R.'' (editorial, Feb. 11):</p>
        <p>That President Bush is no T.R. goes without saying. In 2000, when two oilmen squeaked into office, we had every reason to fear an unprecedented disregard for the natural world, energy efficiency and renewable energy.</p>
        <p>A strong clue was given on Oct. 3, 2000, by Dick Cheney's disparaging remark ''If you're one of those people who puts solar panels on your house or drives a battery-powered car, you might as well vote for Gore.''</p>
        <p>I qualified on both points and followed his instructions.</p>
        <p>Robert Siebert  Orange, Calif., Feb. 11, 2007</p>
      </block>
